1) In the table for substrings of length 5 (positions 1–5 = t23 t28 t22 t21 t27) the nonterminal NT5 appears.  
2) In the table for substrings of length 2 (positions 6–7 = t18 t9) the nonterminal NT8 appears.  
3) Since the start rule is  
  S → NT5 NT8  
we can combine NT5 covering the first 5 symbols with NT8 covering the last 2 symbols to derive the entire string.

A quick check of the terminal‐producing rules shows that the only way to generate the terminal “t8” is by the rule

 NT5 → “t8”

No other nonterminal ever yields a “t8.”  But the start rule is

 S → NT5 NT8

so any “t8” in the derived string must come from the left child (NT5), i.e. at the very beginning of the string.  Since our target string ends in “t8,” the second half (the NT8 part) would have to produce a “t8,” which it cannot.  Therefore the grammar cannot generate the given string.

After attempting a CYK‐style parse (S→NT5 NT8) and seeing that NT5’s only way to yield the initial terminal t8 is via NT5→‘t8’ (so NT5 covers exactly the first symbol), one is forced to try to derive the remaining 11 symbols t4 t10 t27 t18 t8 t11 t21 t18 t29 t4 t6 from NT8.  But none of NT8’s three binary productions (NT8→NT15 NT11, NT8→NT12 NT2, NT8→NT4 NT3) can be coaxed, through their own available terminals and binary splits, into exactly that 11‐token suffix.  Exhausting all splits fails to cover the pattern of terminals in the right order.  Therefore the string is not in L(G).

After inspecting the terminal productions, every symbol in the 12‐token string (t27 t3 t12 t8 t6 t19 t0 t28 t21 t18 t29 t28) appears among the grammar’s terminals.  Moreover, the nonterminals NT5 and NT8 (the two halves of the start production S → NT5 NT8) both participate in mutually recursive cycles and can therefore stretch to cover arbitrarily long substrings, and each of the needed terminals is reachable under these cycles.  Hence the grammar can indeed generate the given string.  

Yes

After inspecting the productions for NT8 (the right half of S → NT5 NT8), you see that every derivation of NT8 either

  • Uses NT8 → NT4 NT3, which yields exactly “t27 t12,” or  
  • Uses NT8 → NT12 NT2 (yielding something t9), or  
  • Uses NT8 → NT15 NT11, whose rightmost terminal must come from NT11 → ’t6’|’t1’|’t28’.

In particular, no NT8 derivation can end in “t19 t12.” But our target string ends with “… t19 t12,” so it cannot be assigned to NT8 at the end of S → NT5 NT8. Hence the string is not in the language.

Consequently there is no way for S→NT5 NT8 to generate  
t19 t29 t21 t12 t6 t29 t21 t4 t8 t22 t12 t10  
in this grammar.

We attempt to build a CYK‐style parse:

1.  S must split into NT5 · NT8.  
2.  To cover the prefix “t19 t23” (positions 1–2), the only NT5‐production that starts with t19 is
       NT5 → NT27 NT18
    with NT27 → ‘t19’ and NT18 → ‘t23’.  
    So NT5 ⇒ “t19 t23” exactly.

3.  That leaves NT8 to cover the 11‐token suffix
       t27  t18  t1  t1  t6  t21  t3  t27  t18  t28  t1  
4.  NT8 has exactly three binary expansions:
       NT8 → NT4 NT3  
       NT8 → NT15 NT11  
       NT8 → NT12 NT2  
    and no direct terminal.

5.  – If NT8 → NT4 NT3, then NT4 must cover the first of those 11, i.e. t27.  NT4 → ‘t27’ is available, so NT4 ⇒ “t27” and NT3 must cover the remaining 10:
         t18  t1  t1  t6  t21  t3  t27  t18  t28  t1.
      Now one checks NT3’s productions:
         NT3 → NT12 NT17  
         NT3 → NT9  NT3  
         NT3 → NT28 NT7  
         NT3 → NT6  NT12  
         NT3 → NT25 NT13  
         NT3 → NT15 NT7  
         NT3 → ‘t12’
      and finds that none of these can generate exactly the 10‑token tail
      starting “t18 t1 …”.  Any attempt to start NT3 with NT12 or NT28 or
      NT9 or NT6 or NT15 etc. either produces the wrong first terminal
      or fails on the second, and the pure‐terminal NT3→‘t12’ is obviously
      wrong.

6.  – The other two splits (NT8→NT15 NT11 or NT8→NT12 NT2) fail immediately
    because NT15 and NT12 cannot yield the third token t27 in single
    or multi‑step expansion without overshooting or mis‐matching the very
    next symbol.

No matter how you try to split the suffix under NT8, you cannot match
the sequence t27 t18 t1 t1 t6 t21 t3 t27 t18 t28 t1.  Therefore there is
no way to build a complete S ⇒* the 13‑token string.

and NT5 can cover the initial t8 (pos 1), but no matter how one tries to split the remaining 12 terminals among NT8’s three CNF productions (NT8→NT15 NT11, NT8→NT12 NT2 or NT8→NT4 NT3) there is no way to derive the tail “t1 t27 t18 t4 t23 t29 t4 t3 t21 t27 t27 t19”. In particular, even short suffixes (of length 2, 3, 4, etc.) fail to match any of NT8’s productions (NT8 → NT15 NT11, NT12 NT2 or NT4 NT3).  Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.

  NT8 → NT15 NT11  
  NT8 → NT12 NT2  
  NT8 → NT4 NT3

none of the possible right‐child expansions can ever end in the terminal “t3” (the only way to get “t3” is from NT24→‘t3’, and NT11, NT2 and NT3 never yield NT24 in the rightmost position).  Since S→NT5 NT8 and our target string ends in “t3”, NT8 would have to generate a suffix ending in t3—which it cannot.  Hence the grammar cannot generate the given string.

  NT8 → NT12 NT2  
  NT8 → NT4 NT3

After attempting to find any valid split in the CYK‐style table and exploring the main top‐level rule S → NT5 NT8, one can see that S can indeed derive a length‑13 terminal string matching

  t0 t10 t8 t22 t0 t6 t0 t4 t18 t4 t0 t27 t9

by letting NT5 cover the first k tokens (for some k) and NT8 cover the last 13−k, with NT8→NT12 NT2 (NT2→t9) and NT12 expanding to the five‑token sequence t4 t18 t4 t0 t27, while NT5 handles the initial seven.  In particular one valid decomposition is

  S

       |      → NT12   NT2
       |          [t4 t18 t4 t0 t27]
       |               t9
       → NT5 covers [t0 t10 t8 t22 t0 t6 t0]

and one checks by following the numerous binary‐split rules (e.g. NT5→NT21 NT12, then NT21→t0, NT12→… etc.) that the prefix can indeed be built.  Therefore the grammar does generate the string.

  NT12  NT1

  X → NT12 NT1  
somewhere in the grammar.  A scan of every binary rule shows no rule whose right‐hand side is NT12 NT1, so there is no way even to begin a parse covering the first two tokens.  Hence the grammar cannot generate the entire 14‐token string.
